For the falling mass, take east as \(x\), up as \(z\), and at the equator \(\boldsymbol{\Omega}\) points north. Since \(v_z=-gt\), the Coriolis acceleration is eastward with magnitude \(a_x=2\omega gt\). Integrating twice gives \(x(t)=\frac13\omega g t^3\), with fall time \(T=\sqrt{2H/g}\).

For the tank, use Bernoulli and continuity with \(A_2\ll A_1\), so the water surface speed is negligible. In part (b)(iii), the submerged air tube makes the pressure at its lower end atmospheric while the water level is above \(H/2\), giving constant effective head \(H/2\) until the level reaches the tube.

\[
\boxed{(a)(i)\ \text{The projectile is deflected eastward, in the direction of Earth's rotation.}}
\]

\[
\boxed{(a)(ii)\ \Delta x=\frac13\omega g\left(\frac{2H}{g}\right)^{3/2}=\frac{2\sqrt2}{3}\frac{\omega H^{3/2}}{\sqrt g}\ \text{eastward, where }g\text{ is gravitational acceleration.}}
\]

\[
\boxed{(a)(iii)\ \text{For }H=1.5\,\text{km},\ \omega=7.29\times10^{-5}\,\text{s}^{-1},\ g=9.81\,\text{m/s}^2:\ \Delta x\approx 1.28\,\text{m eastward}.}
\]

\[
\boxed{(b)(i)\ v(h)=\sqrt{2gh}\ \text{for }A_2\ll A_1,\text{ where }h\text{ is the water height above the spigot.}}
\]

\[
\boxed{(b)(ii)\ t_{\rm drain}=\frac{A_1}{A_2}\sqrt{\frac{2H}{g}}\ \text{for initial water height }H.}
\]

\[
\boxed{(b)(iii)\ t_{\rm drain}=\frac{3}{2}\frac{A_1}{A_2}\sqrt{\frac{H}{g}},\text{ with the air tube ending at height }H/2\text{ above the spigot.}}
\]
